    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-07-14T07:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-07-14T07:30:00-05:00" n="223"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d223">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">795.00/7—1452: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in India (<persName corresp="#p_BCB1"
                            type="from">Bowles</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d223fn1">This telegram was repeated to London.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>
                            <gloss target="#t_niact1">niact</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New Delhi</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-07-14T18:00:00+05:30"
                            >July 14, 1952—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>170. This morning in discussions with <persName corresp="#p_PNR1"
                        >Pillai</persName> I expressed disappointment over apparent unwillingness
                    Commies at Panmunjom to discuss second approach to prisoner question suggested
                    to <persName corresp="#p_PKM1">Panikkar</persName> by Chi Comm Foreign Office in
                    Peking. I stated that instead of exploring with us various methods of assuring
                    uninfluenced neutral screening of prisoners <pb facs="0442" n="408"
                        xml:id="pg_408"/> who express unwillingness return, Commies still determined
                    all Chinese must be sent back regardless their wishes.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_PNR1">Pillai</persName> said this bears out msg received
                    from Peking Saturday<note n="2" xml:id="d223fn2">July 12.</note> which reported
                    that under persistent further questioning by <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss>
                    Chargé d’ Affaires, Chi Foreign Office without explanation had reversed
                    completely its position on second approach previously suggested to <persName
                        corresp="#p_PKM1">Panikkar</persName>.</p>
                <p>As result,… <persName corresp="#p_NPJ1">Nehru</persName> called mtg Sunday a.m.,
                    at which he and <persName corresp="#p_PKM1">Panikkar</persName> were present.
                        <persName corresp="#p_NPJ1">Nehru</persName> expressed his extreme
                    displeasure and embarrassment, asked <persName corresp="#p_PKM1"
                        >Panikkar</persName> for explanation. <persName corresp="#p_PKM1"
                        >Panikkar</persName> stated that <persName corresp="#p_CEL1">Chou
                        En-lai</persName> had evidently been reversed by <persName
                        corresp="#p_MTTC1">Mao Tse-tung</persName>.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_PNR1">Pillai</persName> stated <gloss target="#t_GOI1"
                        >GOI</gloss> disturbed and annoyed but not discouraged; that still felt Comm
                    Chi want truce; maybe they determined exhaust all possibilities first approach
                    before taking up second. I agreed this possible, but suggested flatness Commie
                    statements would make it increasingly difficult for them modify their position
                    in future even though might wish do so.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_PNR1">Pillai</persName> expressed hope of his govt we
                    would continue maintain patience and continue refrain from any statement which
                    might lessen whatever hope may still exist.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BCB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bowles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
